ATH from the test process by default, so the `entire` binary should be findable.\\n\\n3. **Cursor CLI ALSO manually handles env forwarding** (`e2e/agents/cursor_cli.go` lines 156-171). It explicitly passes `CURSOR_API_KEY`, `PATH`, `HOME`, and `TERM` to tmux. While this creates a nested `env` situation with `NewTmuxSession`, it should not break PATH resolution since both layers forward `PATH`.\\n\\n### What's Actually Different About Cursor CLI\\n\\nComparing `cursor_cli.go` (lines 84-122) with Claude Code's implementation, I notice:\\n\\n1. **Cursor CLI waits for the prompt pattern to reappear** after agent finishes (`s.WaitFor(a.PromptPattern(), timeout)`)\\n2. **Claude Code and other agents follow a similar pattern** for interactive execution\\n\\n### The Real Problem: Post-Commit Hook Timing\\n\\nThe issue appears to be related to **when the post-commit hook fires in cursor-cli's tmux session**:\\n\\n1. When cursor-cli (running in tmux) executes `git commit` internally, the post-commit hook is supposed to fire\\n2. The post-commit hook calls `entire hooks git post-commit 2>/dev/null || true` (see `strategy/hooks.go` line 190)\\n3. The hook is **silent on failure** (`2>/dev/null || true`), so if the `entire` binary lookup fails, there's no error output to diagnose\\n4. The test then waits 15 seconds for the checkpoint branch to advance, but nothing happens because the post-commit hook silently failed\\n\\n### Cursor CLI E2E Agent Differences\\n\\nLooking at the implementation:\\n\\n1. **Interactive mode**: Cursor CLI runs in interactive tmux mode (no `-p` headless flag) to ensure all hooks fire (line 87)\\n2. **Prompt pattern**: Uses `/ commands` as the prompt pattern (line 36)\\n3. **env var forwarding**: Only passes specific env vars: `CURSOR_API_KEY`, `PATH`, `HOME`, `TERM` (line 159-162)\\n4. **CI handling**: Unsets the `CI` environment variable (line 169)\\n\\n### Why Other Agents Might Pass\\n\\n**Claude Code, Gemini CLI, OpenCode, Copilot CLI** may pass these tests because:\\n\\n1. They might not actually make commits during the E2E test prompts (agents just create files, user manually commits)\\n2. OR they have better PATH/environment propagation\\n3. OR the test timeout is more forgiving with their timing\\n\\n### Hook System Architecture\\n\\nThe key files involved:\\n\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/hooks.go` - Installs git hooks globally with `entire` command in PATH\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go` - `PostCommit()` implementation that condenses sessions\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/e2e/agents/cursor_cli.go` - Cursor CLI E2E adapter with manual env setup\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/e2e/agents/tmux.go` - Generic TmuxSession that forwards PATH\\n\\n### Likely Solution Areas (For Future Work)\\n\\n1. **Ensure `entire` binary is in PATH**: Make sure `E2E_ENTIRE_BIN` gets added to PATH in the test setup, or use `--absolute-git-hook-path` flag when installing hooks\\n2. **Add environment variable debugging**: Log which PATH is actually being used when the post-commit hook runs\\n3. **Verify hook execution**: Check if the post-commit hook is actually being invoked in the tmux session (add debug output before `2>/dev/null`)\\n4. **Check git hook manager detection**: Cursor has specific hook manager detection - verify it's compatible with the git hooks system\\n\\nThe issue is **not with the checkpoint advancement logic itself**, but with the **hook infrastructure not properly executing in cursor-cli's specific tmux environment during agent commits**.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: aca612d3a1dc8b89f (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 126043\\ntool_uses: 60\\nduration_ms: 307240</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"f19ae9cc-1534-48bf-aed2-067cb0f50d4e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T19:11:57.303Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"I'm investigating wh